<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="392" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,618,1185]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,307,618,644]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Distribution:</emphasis>
Disjunct distribution, including north of Amazonia of 
<collectingCountry box="[923,991,619,645]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and adjacent 
<collectingCountry box="[1147,1237,619,645]" name="Guyana" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, and the east Orinoco River basin in 
<collectingCountry box="[385,495,655,681]" name="Colombia" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Recoder, R. &amp; Dal Vechio, F. &amp; Marques-Sousa, S. &amp; Teixeira, M. &amp; Silva-Da-Silva, M. &amp; Santos-Jr., A. P. &amp; Ribeiro, S. &amp; Barrio-Amoros, C. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T." box="[511,742,655,681]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="61 - 81" refId="ref18267" refString="Recoder, R., Dal Vechio, F., Marques-Sousa, S., Teixeira, M., Silva-Da-Silva, M., Santos-Jr., A. P., Ribeiro, S., Barrio-Amoros, C. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T. (2018) Geographic variation and taxonomy of red-tailed Gymnophthalmus (Squamata: Gymnophthalmidae) from Amazonian Savannas. Zootaxa, 4497 (1), 61 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4497.1.4" type="journal article" year="2018">
Recoder 
<emphasis box="[616,674,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Medina-Rangel, G. F. &amp; Mendez-Galeano, M. A. &amp; Calderon-Espinosa, M. L." box="[755,1074,655,681]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="75 - 90" refId="ref17437" refString="Medina-Rangel, G. F., Mendez-Galeano, M. A. &amp; Calderon-Espinosa, M. L. (2019) Herpetofauna of San Jose del Guaviare, Guaviare, Colombia. Biota Colombiana, 20 (1), 75 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.21068 / c 2019. v 20 n 01 a 05" type="journal article" year="2019">
Medina-Rangel 
<emphasis box="[939,997,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">et al.</emphasis>
, 2019
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1126,1236,655,681]" name="Colombia" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Colombia</collectingCountry>
there are records from 
<collectingRegion box="[213,297,691,717]" country="Colombia" name="Arauca" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Arauca</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[307,410,691,717]" country="Colombia" name="Casanare" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Casanare</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[465,568,691,717]" country="Colombia" name="Guaviare" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Guaviare</collectingRegion>
departments (
<figureCitation box="[726,814,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution maps for the cis-Andean microteiid lizards in Colombia (Alopoglossidae + Gymnophthalmidae). Circles are examined specimens, while squares are records from literature (see Supplementary Files for specific references). Red arrows indicate new records for Colombia. Black arrows show a zoom in to regions where several records overlap. The light green shadow indicates the Orinoco River basin, and the dark green the Amazon River basin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5681929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5681929/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,618,1185]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,386,726,752]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Similar species:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" box="[393,735,727,753]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis box="[393,735,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Gymnophthalmus leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mainly distinguished from its congeners of the region based on coloration pattern, which consists of a white upper lip (black in 
<taxonomicName box="[922,1040,763,789]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis box="[922,1040,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); white or cream belly (dark in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">G. cryptus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and dark with white reticulations in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hallowell" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[668,811,799,825]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis box="[668,811,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group); vivid dorsolateral stripe that extends from the supraocular region to the base of the tail (inconspicuous stripe that fades away towards the midbody in 
<taxonomicName box="[1319,1436,835,861]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis box="[1319,1436,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hallowell" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[197,337,871,897]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis box="[197,337,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, continuously extending beyond the base of the tail in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[1009,1192,871,897]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[1009,1192,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and grey tail (bluish in 
<taxonomicName box="[181,299,907,933]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis box="[181,299,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, salmon-pink in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[493,680,907,933]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[493,680,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and reddish in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hallowell" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[866,1008,907,933]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis box="[866,1008,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" box="[1262,1436,907,933]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis box="[1262,1436,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may also be differentiated in having a temporal formula 3+2+2, with the occipital scale in contact only with the superior temporal of the third row (temporal formula 3+2+1, with the occipital scale in contact with the temporals of both the third and second rows in 
<taxonomicName box="[557,672,1015,1041]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis box="[557,672,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[726,910,1015,1041]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[726,910,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). For a more detailed description see 
<bibRefCitation author="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; de Carvalho, C. M." pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="173 - 226" refId="ref19784" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; de Carvalho, C. M. (1991) Two sibling and sympatric species of Gymnophthalmus in Roraima, Brasil (Sauria: Teiidae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, Sao Paulo, 37 (12), 173 - 226." type="journal article" year="1991">Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho (1991)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="392" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,618,1185]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1087,1113]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" box="[325,667,1087,1113]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis box="[325,667,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Gymnophthalmus leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recently reported for the first time in 
<collectingCountry box="[1144,1257,1087,1113]" name="Colombia" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, in San José del 
<collectingRegion box="[151,256,1123,1149]" country="Colombia" name="Guaviare" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Guaviare</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[269,372,1123,1149]" country="Colombia" name="Guaviare" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Guaviare</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Medina-Rangel, G. F. &amp; Mendez-Galeano, M. A. &amp; Calderon-Espinosa, M. L." box="[388,700,1123,1149]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="75 - 90" refId="ref17437" refString="Medina-Rangel, G. F., Mendez-Galeano, M. A. &amp; Calderon-Espinosa, M. L. (2019) Herpetofauna of San Jose del Guaviare, Guaviare, Colombia. Biota Colombiana, 20 (1), 75 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.21068 / c 2019. v 20 n 01 a 05" type="journal article" year="2019">
Medina-Rangel 
<emphasis box="[573,630,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). Here, we include three additional locations for this species and extend its current distribution ca. 
<quantity box="[528,613,1158,1185]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" unit="km" value="525.0">525 km</quantity>
NE to the previous northernmost known record in 
<collectingCountry box="[1184,1298,1159,1185]" name="Colombia" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Colombia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
